<title type="html"><![CDATA[Mandelbrot / Fractals in 6502?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3524&amp;p=26546#p26546"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">doppelganger wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Since Julia sets use a fixed point and the Mandelbrot set uses every point, it can be said that the Mandelbrot set is an index to every possible Julia set.  I will even go so far as to say the Mandelbrot set *is* every Julia set mashed up together in one fractal universe.<br /></div><br />You'd be correct. The Mandelbrot set was invented as a way to test conjectures about the set of Julia sets. Wikipedia <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandelbrot_set#Formal_definition" class="postlink">states</a> that "it is the subset of the complex plane consisting of those parameters c for which the Julia set of fc is connected."<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon Aug 27, 2007 8:19 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
